## Problem

Review of hypercerts-ars.1 (commit 722067d) found that `recordDateString` is still timezone-dependent for full UTC ISO strings.

The fix added a regex guard for date-only strings (`/^\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}$/`) which correctly returns them as-is. However, when `record.startDate` is a full UTC ISO string like `"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z"` (a format the SDK uses ŌĆö see SDK docs examples), the fallback path does:

```ts
const d = new Date("2024-01-01T00:00:00Z"); // UTC midnight
d.getDate(); // returns 31 in UTC-5 timezone ŌåÆ "2023-12-31" Ō£Ś
```

This is the same class of bug as the original: local time extraction from a UTC-anchored Date is still timezone-dependent. In any UTC-N timezone, UTC midnight becomes the previous calendar day locally.

## Evidence

The `@hypercerts-org/sdk-core` type docs show both formats in use:
- `startDate: "2024-01-01T00:00:00Z"` (full UTC ISO ŌĆö used in older records)
- `startDate: "2024-01-01"` (date-only ŌĆö handled correctly by the regex guard)

The acceptance criterion `recordDateString("2026-01-15T00:00:00+14:00") returns "2026-01-15"` only passes in UTC+14 timezone. In UTC+0 or any UTC-N timezone it returns `"2026-01-14"`.

## Fix

Extend the regex guard to also handle ISO strings by extracting the date portion directly from the string (no `new Date()` parsing needed):

```ts
const recordDateString = (raw: string | undefined | null): string => {
  if (!raw) return "";
  // Date-only string ŌĆö return as-is
  if (/^\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}$/.test(raw)) return raw;
  // ISO string with time component ŌĆö extract date portion from the string directly
  // (avoids timezone-dependent local extraction)
  const isoMatch = raw.match(/^(\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2})T/);
  if (isoMatch) return isoMatch[1];
  // Fallback for other formats (unusual) ŌĆö local extraction
  const d = new Date(raw);
  const y = d.getFullYear();
  const m = String(d.getMonth() + 1).padStart(2, "0");
  const day = String(d.getDate()).padStart(2, "0");
  return `${y}-${m}-${day}`;
};
```

