## File
app/api/oauth/callback/route.ts, line 45

## Problem
The return_to parameter is validated with:
```ts
const redirectPath = returnTo.startsWith('/') ? returnTo : '/';
```

This check is bypassed by protocol-relative URLs like `//evil.com/path`. The string `//evil.com` starts with `/`, so it passes the guard. When passed to `new URL(redirectPath, config.baseUrl)`, Node's URL constructor treats `//evil.com` as a protocol-relative URL and resolves it to `https://evil.com` ŌĆö an open redirect to an attacker-controlled domain.

## Reproduction
1. Attacker crafts: `/api/oauth/callback?code=...&state=...&return_to=//evil.com`
2. `returnTo.startsWith('/')` ŌåÆ true
3. `new URL('//evil.com', 'https://myapp.com')` ŌåÆ `https://evil.com`
4. User is redirected to attacker's site after login

## Fix
Replace the startsWith check with a URL-parse-based validation that ensures the resolved URL stays on the same origin:
```ts
function safeReturnTo(returnTo: string, baseUrl: string): string {
  try {
    const resolved = new URL(returnTo, baseUrl);
    const base = new URL(baseUrl);
    return resolved.origin === base.origin ? resolved.pathname + resolved.search : '/';
  } catch {
    return '/';
  }
}
const redirectPath = safeReturnTo(returnTo, config.baseUrl);
```

This rejects any return_to that resolves to a different origin, including protocol-relative URLs, absolute URLs, and data: URIs.

